**Report Structure**

    This 100 Mbps link at Nagpur CFA shows extremely low average usage (0.53 Mbps), indicating significant under-utilization. While business hours are slightly busier (1.22 Mbps), overall traffic remains minimal. There are rare, very short bursts, with one instance reaching 98.28 Mbps, nearly maxing out the link for a single minute. Most of the time, usage is well below 7 Mbps.

2.  **Capacity Planning Recommendations**
    The link is heavily over-provisioned for its typical demand. Sustained daily peaks average only 3.13 Mbps. Despite an 11.60% monthly growth, current capacity is projected to last for thousands of months. Consider rightsizing the link based on sustained usage patterns, while accounting for the rare, high-speed bursts.

3.  **Performance Risks & Bottlenecks**
    Currently, there are no congestion risks for regular traffic. The single high peak of 98.28 Mbps demonstrates the link can handle near-full capacity bursts without exceeding the provisioned limit. This indicates efficient handling of occasional high-demand events, but these are not frequent enough to cause sustained bottlenecks.

**Conclusion**
The link is significantly over-provisioned and can be optimized for cost efficiency.
